description: From Middle English mōt, ȝemōt, from Old English *mōt, ġemōt (“meeting”), from Proto-Germanic [Term?], from Proto-Indo-European *meh₂d- (“to encounter, come”). Cognate with Scots mut, mote (“meeting, assembly”), Low German Mööt (“meeting”), Moot (“meeting”), archaic Dutch (ge)moet (“meeting”), Danish møde (“meeting”), Swedish möte (“meeting”), Norwegian møte (“meeting”), Icelandic mót (“meeting, tournament, meet”). Related to meet.

adjectives.description: moot (comparative more moot, superlative most moot)

entries.meaning: (current in UK, rare in the US) Subject to discussion (originally at a moot); arguable, debatable, unsolved or impossible to solve.
examples: […] :indeed we were obligd to hawl off rather in a hurry for the wind freshning a little we found ourselves in a bay which it was a moot point whether or not we could get out of: […]

entries.meaning: (Canada, US, chiefly law) Being an exercise of thought; academic.
(Canada, US) Having no practical consequence or relevance.
examples: Synonyms: irrelevant, (if it was previously relevant) obsolete
That point may make for a good discussion, but it is moot.

entries.meaning: A moot court.
examples: The pleading used in courts and chancery called moots.

entries.meaning: A system of arbitration in many areas of Africa in which the primary goal is to settle a dispute and reintegrate adversaries into society rather than assess penalties.
(Scouting) A gathering of Rovers, usually in the form of a camp lasting 2 weeks.
(paganism) A social gathering of pagans, normally held in a public house.
(historical) An assembly (usually for decision-making in a locality). [from the 12th c.]
(shipbuilding) A ring for gauging wooden pins.

description: From Middle English moten (“to speak, talk, converse, discuss”), from Old English mōtian (“to speak, converse, discuss”). See also mutter (which is a frequentative of moot).

entries.meaning: (Scotland, Northern England) A whisper, or an insinuation, also gossip or rumors.
examples: Na, I haven't heard a moot of it.
Haven't you heard the moot, mate? There are going to be layoffs.

entries.meaning: (Scotland, Northern England, rural) Talk.
examples: No, there's no moot of it on the streets.
There's some moot of charges, but nothing concrete yet.

verbs.description: moot (third-person singular simple present moots, present participle mooting, simple past and past participle mooted)

entries.meaning: To bring up as a subject for debate, to propose.
To discuss or debate.
examples: a problem which hardly has been mentioned, far less mooted, in this country

entries.meaning: (US) To make or declare irrelevant.
To argue or plead in a supposed case.
examples: There is a difference between mooting and pleading; between fencing and fighting.

entries.meaning: (regional, obsolete) To talk or speak.
examples: 'Tis no boot to moot again of it.

entries.meaning: (Scotland, Northern England) To say, utter, also insinuate.
examples: He could not moot the words.

entries.meaning: (Australia) Vagina.
(West Country) The stump of a tree; the roots and bottom end of a felled tree.

verbs.description: moot (third-person singular simple present moots, present participle mooting, simple past and past participle mooted)

entries.meaning: (West Country) To take root and begin to grow.
(West Country) To turn up soil or dig up roots, especially an animal with a snout.

description: Clipping of mutual with humorously altered pronunciation.

entries.meaning: (Internet slang, endearing) A mutual follower on a social media platform.
examples: Eid Mubarak to all my muslim moots out there
